AllLife Bank Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

Olaf Shibusawa¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer, based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank, using clustering algorithms, and provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

Data Description¶

-Sl_No. Primary key of the recor
-Customer Key: Customer identification number
-Average Credit Limit: Average credit limit of each customer for all credit cards
-Total credit cards: Total number of credit cards possessed by the customer
-Total visits bank: Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank
-Total visits online: Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)
-Total calls made: Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(12, 8), bins=None):
    """Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (10,6)
    bins: number of bins (default None/auto)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,
        sharex=True,
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )
    sns.boxplot(feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="lightblue")
    sns.distplot(
        feature, kde=F, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="pastel"
    ) if bins else sns.distplot(feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2, color="red")
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        np.mean(feature), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        np.median(feature), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

K-Means Clustering¶

Apply K-means Clustering¶

In [22]:
## We will use the Elbow Method for determining the optimal number of clusters (k)

# Range of clusters to be fed to K-means clustering algorithm
clusters = range(1, 10)
# list to store the average distortion for each k clusters.
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    # create the K-means model with k clusters
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    # fitting the scaled data to the K-means moldel
    model.fit(scaled_df)
    # predict the closest cluster each sample in dfScaled belongs to
    prediction = model.predict(scaled_df)
    # computing the average distortion
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(scaled_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / scaled_df.shape[0]
    )
    # adding the distortion of the current K-means with k clusters to the list
    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)
# Plotting the average distorion for each k clusters K-means model
plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k With The Elbow Method")
plt.show()

Silhouette Score¶

Silhouette Score is a metric used to evaluate the quality of clustering results, such as those obtained through the k-means algorithm. It measures how well each data point fits into its assigned cluster based on the distance to points in its own cluster (cohesion) and the distance to points in the nearest neighboring cluster (separation). A higher silhouette score indicates that the clustering results are more compact and well-separated.

A silhouette score of 1 indicates that the data points are well-clustered, meaning that they are closer to the other points in their own cluster than to any points in other clusters. This is the ideal scenario.

A score of 0 means that the data points are close to the boundary between two clusters, indicating that the clustering is not clearly defined or that there may be overlapping clusters.

A score of -1 means that the data points are assigned to the wrong cluster, indicating that the clustering is completely incorrect.

In [23]:
sil_score = []
cluster_list = list(range(2, 10))
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters)
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((scaled_df))
    # centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    score = silhouette_score(scaled_df, preds)
    sil_score.append(score)
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {}".format(n_clusters, score))

plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")
plt.xlabel("n_clusters")
plt.title("Using Silhouette Score to Determine k", fontsize=16)

plt.plot(cluster_list, sil_score)

  • According to the graph and the score, 3 looks like the optimal number for k followed by 4.
  • The score for 3 clusters is 0.52 which means that the clustering algorithm has done a reasonably good job in grouping similar data points together and separating dissimilar ones into different clusters.
  • The score for 4 clusters is 0.36 indicating that that there is some overlap between the clusters or that the distances between data points in different clusters are not well-separated.

    • Customers in this cluster have the highest number of Total_calls_made and the largest range of the same (from 1 to 10).
    • It has the smallest number of Total_Credits_Cards and Avg_Credit_Limit.
  • Cluster 1:
    • Customers in this cluster had the highest Total_visits_bank and the largest number of customers.
    • It also has the smallest number of Total_visits_online.
    • Although the median Avg_Credit_Limit is at around 34,000, it spans up to 100,000.
  • Cluster 2:
    • Customers in this cluster have the hightest Avg_Credit_Limit, Total_Credit_Cards and Total_visits_online.
    • With respect to number of credit cards it's upper limit is 10 compared to 4 and 10 for clusters 0 and 1 respectively.
    • These customers have the lowest Total_visits_bank and Total_calls_made.
    • This is also the smallest cluster with 50 customers.

Hierarchical Clustering¶

Above we applied K Means Clustering, and here we will apply Hierarchical Clustering. These are some of the differences between the two:

Methodology: K-means clustering is a centroid-based clustering method, where each cluster is represented by a centroid (the center point of all the points in the cluster), while hierarchical clustering is a linkage-based clustering method, which creates a hierarchical tree-like structure of clusters based on the similarity between data points.

Number of clusters: In K-means clustering, the number of clusters needs to be specified in advance, while in hierarchical clustering, the number of clusters is determined by the structure of the hierarchical tree.

Flexibility: Hierarchical clustering is more flexible than K-means clustering in terms of the types of distances or dissimilarities used to group data points.

Interpretability: Hierarchical clustering provides a visual representation of the clustering structure in the form of a dendrogram, which allows for easy interpretation of the relationship between clusters. K-means clustering does not provide such a visualization.

Scalability: K-means clustering is faster and more scalable than hierarchical clustering for large datasets.

Overall, the choice between K-means clustering and hierarchical clustering depends on the specific problem at hand, the size of the dataset, and the desired level of interpretability.

Cophenetic Corelation Analysis¶

The cophenetic correlation coefficient is a measure of the correlation between the cophenetic distances and the original distances of the objects. The cophenetic distance between two objects is the height of the node where they first join together in the dendrogram.

The coefficient ranges from 0 to 1, where a value of 1 indicates a perfect match between the dendrogram and the original distances. Higher values of the coefficient indicate better agreement between the dendrogram and the original distances, while lower values indicate poorer agreement. In general, a coefficient above 0.7 is considered to be a good match, while values below 0.5 indicate a poor match.

A higher coefficient indicates that the dendrogram accurately represents the original distances between the objects and is a good representation of the data. Conversely, a lower coefficient suggests that the dendrogram may not be a good representation of the underlying structure of the data.

distance_metrics = [
    "canberra",

    "cityblock",

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["complete", "average", "single", "weighted"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(scaled_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(scaled_df))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

Dendogram Visualization¶

Now we will look at Dendograms for the different linkage methods

In [39]:
# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]

# lists to save results of cophenetic correlation calculation
compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]
compare = []

# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage methods above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(scaled_df, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(scaled_df))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

SUMMARY¶

Comparison of K Means Clustering to Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • As stated before an issue with the Hierarchical Clustering with 4 clusters is that we ended up with a cluster that only has one customer in it. To overcome this issue we reran it with three clusters but still ended up with that same lone cluster.
  • We recommend to rerun the hierarchical analysis with Manhattan distance which is less sensitive to outliers which we have in some features. We could also keep the analysis with Euclidian but with different linkage types different from Average linkage to see if we can improve the clustering.
  • The Hierarchical analysis took longer than K Means beacuse of the dendograms, this would be more of a problem with larger data sets but in this instance with only 660 records and several columns it was not a big impact.

Business Comments and Recommendations (based on K Means Analysis)¶

  • We recommend classifying the customer base into 3 clusters.
  • Cluster 0: -This is the cluster with the highest number of Total_calls_made and the largest range of the same (from 1 to 10). Targetting these customers with a marketing campaign to encourage online banking would be beneficial and reduce calls to the call center which is expensive compared to online.
    • This cluster also has the lowest Total_Credits_Cards and Avg_Credit_Limit but it is not shown that increasing their credit limits of number of credit cards would decrease call center calls.
  • Cluster 1:
    • Customers in this cluster had the highest Total_visits_bank and the largest number of customers. It also had the lowest Total_visits_online. As in Cluster 0, it would be benefcial to target these customers with a marketing campaign to encourage online banking would be beneficial and visits to the bank thereby reducing costs. Since this is the largest cluster, we could have a big impact targetting this segment.
  • Cluster 2:
    • This cluster has the highest Total_visits_online and it is the smallest cluster as well so it does not make sense to make this cluster a priority for any marketing campaigns for existing customers. However, this cluster is an excellent opprtunity for people who are not yet customers because they are low cost and since they have the highest number of credit cards they are high yield customers.
